      "creation_date" : 1403892006,
      "post_id" : 2721672,
      "comment_id" : 37849759,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "I think the question here is &quot;why&quot;. Why do generics require Objects? The consensus appears to be that it&#39;s less of a design choice and more caving in to backward compatibility. In my eyes, if generics can&#39;t handle primitives, that&#39;s a functionality deficit. As it stands, everything involving primitives has to be written for each primitive: instead of Comparator&lt;t,t&gt;, we have Integer.compare(int a, int b), Byte.compare(byte a, byte b), etc. That&#39;s not a solution!"
    }, {
      "owner" : {
